Part 3

Ramanna asked him on the fifth morning, formally, standing straighter on the stone verandah than Vikram had yet seen him stand. 

"Sir," the caretaker said, his hands folded in front of his chest. "My daughter Lakshmi's marriage is the day after tomorrow. You are staying under my roof, and it would be my honor if you attend the ceremony."

"I don't want to intrude on your family's space," Vikram said, looking at the invitation.

"Intrude?" Ramanna looked genuinely wounded by the word, his shoulders dropping slightly. "You are staying in my house, sir. If you don't come, the whole village will ask what is wrong with my hospitality and why the big company boss is hiding."

Vikram went.

---

The wedding took over the entire dirt lane outside Ramanna's small house. 

A pandal of bamboo poles and colored cloth had been thrown up in two days, with green banana stems tied to every entrance pillar, and fresh mango leaves strung across the gate in lines that dipped and rose in the warm breeze.

Somebody put a heavy paper plate into Vikram's hands before he had even finished taking off his leather shoes near the verandah steps.

"Eat, eat," said a middle-aged woman he hadn't been introduced to. She ladled a second helping of hot, steaming sambar onto his banana leaf before he could protest that he hadn't finished the first portion. "You have come from so far away, from the city. You must eat properly in this house."

He tried explaining that he was only staying at the plantation for two more days, but she didn't appear to hear that part of his sentence over the noise of the crowd.

---

By the second course of the meal, Vikram had been fed by at least four different aunts, each one convinced the previous three had not given him enough food. 

An uncle with a red, paan-stained smile sat beside him and remarked that he looked "too thin for a business tycoon, no offense intended, sir." Vikram found, to his own surprise, that he didn't take the comment as an insult.

The wedding ceremony itself happened in pieces that Vikram could only half follow. 

He watched the priest's Sanskrit chants run fast and rhythmic over the sacrificial fire, the smoke rising toward the cloth roof. He saw the bride, Lakshmi, wearing heavy temple gold jewelry that looked far too heavy for her thin wrists, and her new husband's hands shaking slightly as he tied the yellow thread of the mangalsutra. 

There was a sudden, loud roar of conch shells and women's ululation that made Vikram's ears ring pleasantly for a full minute after the knot was tied.

Nobody in the crowd asked him for anything. Nobody wanted a corporate license signed, a new labor policy explained, or a board of directors satisfied. 

They simply wanted him to eat more rice and curry, which he found himself doing without any hesitation.

---

On the second evening of the festivities, Vikram sat on Ramanna's verandah with his mobile phone pressed against his ear. He could hear the brass wedding band still playing some movie tunes somewhere down the lane behind him.

"Sir, the minister's office has confirmed the meeting for Thursday morning," his assistant's voice said from the speaker. "Reddy sir has traveled from Hyderabad and will meet you at the gate directly."

"Good," Vikram said.

"Also, sir... are you well? Your voice sounds different on the phone."

Vikram considered several ways of answering that statement that were completely true. "I have been eating a lot of sambar," he said finally.

His assistant, after a brief pause of confusion, decided not to ask any further questions. Vikram appreciated that silence more than she probably knew.

---

Ramanna found him on the steps after the call ended. He was carrying two glasses of hot, over-sweet tea, and he settled onto the concrete step beside Vikram without waiting to be invited. 

It was the way only a man who has decided you now belong a little to his household would sit.

"Good wedding?" Vikram asked, taking the hot glass.

"Good wedding," Ramanna agreed, blowing on his tea. He added the only compliment he seemed to consider worth giving: "You ate properly, at least. My wife was worried that a big company man from Calcutta wouldn't touch our village food."

"It was better than anything the board canteens serve," Vikram said, taking a sip of the sweet tea.

Ramanna laughed—a short, surprised bark of a laugh, as if he hadn't expected the city boss to tell the truth. 

They sat together on the step for a long time, saying nothing else. Behind them, the brass band worked through the same four wedding songs for the third time that night, and neither man minded the noise in the least.

[End of Part 3]
